     NNNNaaaammmmeeee
          MAPMEM - Displays memory module information

     SSSSyyyynnnnttttaaaaxxxx
          mmmmaaaappppmmmmeeeemmmm [ ----ddddeeeemmmmpppprrrrsssstttt!!!!????hhhh ] [ >>>>[>>>>]]]] _f_i_l_e | _d_e_v_i_c_e ]
          [ ; _n_e_x_t _c_o_m_m_a_n_d ]

     DDDDeeeessssccccrrrriiiippppttttiiiioooonnnn
          _M_a_p_m_e_m displays one or more tables describing the drivers
          and other memory modules that are present in memory.  These
          modules are identified by function and are displayed in one
          of three categories: disk drivers, character drivers or
          filters, and other modules.

          By default, _m_a_p_m_e_m displays four sections of information.
          The first is a summary indicating how much low and high RAM
          is available and how much low RAM was available when the
          system booted.  The next section shows the drivers that are
          used for each enabled logical drive.  The third section
          displays the drivers and filters that are connected to each
          character device.

          The final section displays memory modules that are not
          directly accessed as a logical drive or character device.
          These modules may contain patches to the system, or contain
          code shared by one or more of the other drives.  There are
          other possible uses for these memory modules.

          When a memory module is displayed, the following information
          is displayed:
          1.    The starting address of the memory module in
                hexadecimal.
          2.    The ending address of the memory module in
                hexadecimal.
          3.    The length of the memory module (in hexadecimal or
                decimal).
          4.    The name of the memory module.
          5.    A short description of the purpose of the memory
                module.

          _M_a_p_m_e_m accepts several options.  Options are specified by
          single characters, and they may be entered in upper or
          lowercase.  Options are always preceded by a hyphen (a "-").
          If you are specifying multiple options, you can specify the
          options in any of these formats:
                -a -b -c   or   -abc   or   -a -bc   or  -ab -c

          The options are:

          ----dddd   The length of memory modules is displayed in decimal.
               By default the value is displayed in hexadecimal.




