     NNNNooootttteeeessss
          Memory modules that _m_a_p_m_e_m displays in the "other" category
          may actually be one of the parts of a disk or character
          driver.  This is often done to share code that is used in
          other drivers.  The _D_i_s_k_D_i_s_k product creates one small
          memory module for each logical drive and a single, larger
          memory module that contains code that is shared by all the
          DiskDisk logical drives.

          _M_a_p_m_e_m relies on the headers of the various memory modules
          that are present on the system to be formatted correctly.
          If these are corrupted, _m_a_p_m_e_m may display warnings or
          display incorrect information.


     FFFFiiiilllleeeessss
          _M_a_p_m_e_m reads the MMMMAAAAPPPPMMMMEEEEMMMM////IIIINNNNIIII file to provide the descriptions
          of the memory modules that are displayed.  The user may add
          additional descriptions to this file if needed.  A maximum
          of 50 entries may be placed in the MMMMAAAAPPPPMMMMEEEEMMMM////IIIINNNNIIII file.  The
          descriptions are limited to 35 characters. See the
          MMMMAAAAPPPPMMMMEEEEMMMM////IIIINNNNIIII file for formatting details.

          _M_a_p_m_e_m also examines the DDDDEEEEFFFFAAAAUUUULLLLTTTTSSSS////MMMMAAAADDDD file and uses any
          default options that are specified there.  For example, if
          you wanted _m_a_p_m_e_m to omit the headers by default, the
          following entry in the DDDDEEEEFFFFAAAAUUUULLLLTTTTSSSS////MMMMAAAADDDD file would do this:
                      MAPMEM -T
          Options in the DDDDEEEEFFFFAAAAUUUULLLLTTTTSSSS////MMMMAAAADDDD file are ignored if the ----!!!!
          option is specified on the command line.

          You may make copies of _m_a_p_m_e_m with different names.  When
          examining the DDDDEEEEFFFFAAAAUUUULLLLTTTTSSSS////MMMMAAAADDDD file, the name used to invoke the
          program will be used to locate the default entries.  For
          example, if you made copies of MMMMAAAAPPPPMMMMEEEEMMMM////CCCCMMMMDDDD and named them
          DDDDRRRRIIIIVVVVEEEESSSS////CCCCMMMMDDDD and RRRRAAAAMMMM////CCCCMMMMDDDD, you could add the following lines to
          the DDDDEEEEFFFFAAAAUUUULLLLTTTTSSSS////MMMMAAAADDDD file:
                      DRIVES -R
                      RAM -S
          When _d_r_i_v_e_s is run, information on active logical drives
          would be displayed and nothing else.  When _r_a_m is run, the
          information on RAM availability would be displayed and
          nothing else.


